</tr>
</table>

<h3>Category B: Correct (No Changes Needed)</h3>

<p>20+ Result files already follow the proper convention: PascalCase filenames with snake_case declarations (e.g., <code>AiModelConfig.pm</code> correctly declares <code>ai_model_config</code>). These require no changes.</p>

<h2>Implementation Plan</h2>

<h3>Phase 1: Update Result File Declarations (Code Changes Only)</h3>

<p><strong>Scope</strong>: 4 Result files requiring declaration fix</p>
<p><strong>Risk Level</strong>: VERY LOW - Code-only changes, no database impact</p>

<ol>
<li><code>Comserv/lib/Comserv/Model/Schema/Ency/Result/CodeSearchIndex.pm</code>
  <ul>
  <li>Line 5: Change <code>__PACKAGE__->table('codesearchindex');</code> to <code>__PACKAGE__->table('code_search_index');</code></li>
  </ul>
</li>
<li><code>Comserv/lib/Comserv/Model/Schema/Ency/Result/DocumentationMetadataIndex.pm</code>
  <ul>
  <li>Line 5: Change <code>__PACKAGE__->table('documentationmetadataindex');</code> to <code>__PACKAGE__->table('documentation_metadata_index');</code></li>
  </ul>
</li>
<li><code>Comserv/lib/Comserv/Model/Schema/Ency/Result/WebSearchResult.pm</code>
  <ul>
  <li>Line 5: Change <code>__PACKAGE__->table('websearchresult');</code> to <code>__PACKAGE__->table('web_search_result');</code></li>
  </ul>
</li>
<li><code>Comserv/lib/Comserv/Model/Schema/Ency/Result/SiteDomain.pm</code>
  <ul>
  <li>Line 4: Change <code>__PACKAGE__->table('sitedomain');</code> to <code>__PACKAGE__->table('site_domain');</code></li>
  </ul>
</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Testing After Phase 1</strong>: Verify Perl module compilation and DBIx::Class schema loading without errors.</p>

<h3>Phase 2: Update Database Table Names (if required)</h3>

<p><strong>Prerequisites</strong>: Phase 1 code changes must be deployed and tested</p>

<ol>
<li>Determine if database tables exist with old names (query MySQL information_schema)</li>
<li>Create migration script: <code>Comserv/script/migrate_table_names.pl</code></li>
<li>Execute migrations with full backup and validation</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Database Alterations (if old tables exist)</strong>:</p>

<pre>
ALTER TABLE codesearchindex RENAME TO code_search_index;
ALTER TABLE documentationmetadataindex RENAME TO documentation_metadata_index;
ALTER TABLE websearchresult RENAME TO web_search_result;
ALTER TABLE sitedomain RENAME TO site_domain;
</pre>

<p><strong>Risk Level</strong>: LOW if tables are only accessed through DBIx::Class (not raw SQL)</p>

<h3>Phase 3: Update Code References</h3>

<p><strong>Locations to Search</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>Comserv/lib/Comserv/Controller/</code> - Any hardcoded table name strings</li>
<li><code>Comserv/root/</code> - Template files with table references</li>
<li>Raw SQL queries (if any) using old table names</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Expected Impact</strong>: MINIMAL - DBIx::Class abstraction should shield most code from table name changes</p>

<h3>Phase 4: Clean Up (Remove Workaround Code)</h3>

<p><strong>Files to Delete</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>Comserv/lib/Comserv/Util/TableNameNormalizer.pm</code> - No longer needed</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Files to Revert in Admin.pm</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Remove import of TableNameNormalizer</li>
<li>Revert <code>build_result_table_mapping()</code> function to standard <code>lc()</code> comparison</li>
<li>Revert <code>compare_table_with_result_file_v2()</code> function to use <code>lc()</code></li>
<li>Revert <code>find_orphaned_result_files_v2()</code> function to use <code>lc()</code></li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Result</strong>: Simple, maintainable code that enforces naming standards without workarounds</p>

<h2>Risks and Mitigations</h2>

<table border="1">
<tr>
<th>Risk</th>
<th>Mitigation</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Database migration failures</td>
<td>Test migrations on database copy, perform full backup before execution, use transactions</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Code references to old table names</td>
<td>Grep search entire codebase before migration, update all references</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Application downtime</td>
<td>Execute migrations during scheduled maintenance window, have rollback plan</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Data loss or corruption</td>
<td>Verify data integrity post-migration with checksums and record counts</td>
</tr>
</table>

<h2>Timeline</h2>

<ul>
<li><strong>Phase 1</strong>: ~30 minutes (4 file updates, compilation test)</li>
<li><strong>Phase 2</strong>: ~1 hour (migration script, backup, database execution)</li>
<li><strong>Phase 3</strong>: ~30 minutes (code search, reference updates)</li>
<li><strong>Phase 4</strong>: ~15 minutes (cleanup, file deletions/reversions)</li>
<li><strong>Total Estimated</strong>: ~2.5 hours</li>
</ul>

<h2>Decision Points</h2>

<ol>
<li><strong>Accept Plan</strong>: Proceed with all phases as outlined</li>
<li><strong>Phase 1 Only</strong>: Start with code-only changes, defer database changes to separate approval</li>
<li><strong>Modify Scope</strong>: Adjust which files are prioritized</li>
<li><strong>Alternative</strong>: Keep normalization workaround (NOT RECOMMENDED - violates standards)</li>
</ol>

<h3>Recommendation</h3>

<p><strong>Approve Phase 1 immediately</strong> (low-risk, code-only changes), then Phase 2-4 after testing in development environment. This allows verification that the changes work without database impact before proceeding to production database changes.</p>

<h2>Note</h2>

<p><strong>Important</strong>: This plan fixes the root cause of schema_compare false positives by enforcing consistent naming conventions from the source (Result file declarations), rather than implementing workaround/normalization logic. This approach eliminates technical debt, improves code quality, and prevents future naming-related issues.</p>
